<!-- 01 INTRO -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">01 · Restaurant wine cellar cooling</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">A restaurant wine cellar at 65°F and 35% humidity is destroying inventory in real time.</h2>

    <p>Wine bottles need 55 to 58°F (red), 50 to 55°F (white), 45 to 50°F (sparkling), AND 50 to 70% relative humidity to preserve corks and prevent oxidation. When the cooling system fails or drifts, premium wine inventory can lose value fast. A $400 Burgundy at 70°F for a week is not the same wine.</p>

    <p>This is not residential wine fridge repair. Restaurant wine rooms use specialized commercial cooling: <strong>Wine Guardian</strong> (most common LA restaurant spec, Quincy IL, premium ducted and ductless systems), <strong>CellarPro</strong> (West Sacramento CA, specialty self-contained units), <strong>KoolR</strong> (premium custom installations), <strong>Breezaire</strong> (entry-tier through-the-wall units), <strong>Vinotemp Commercial</strong> (LA-based, common in hotels). Plus integrated wine displays in dining rooms, typically Sub-Zero 424 series or Hoshizaki HR commercial reach-ins.</p>

    <p>We service commercial wine cellar cooling across LA, Orange, Ventura, San Bernardino, Riverside counties. EPA 608 Universal certified. BHGS #A49573. BBB A+. Phones answered 24/7 because wine cellar failures are inventory-protection emergencies.</p>

    <p>For residential wine cellar service (smaller installations, $89 residential diagnostic, single-zone or dual-zone), see <a href="/services/wine-cellar-repair/">residential wine cellar repair</a>. This page covers commercial restaurant and hospitality scope at the $120 commercial diagnostic.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 02 TYPICAL FAILURES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">02 · Typical wine cellar cooling failures</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we diagnose most often on commercial wine cellars.</h2>

    <ol class="failure-list">
      <li><strong>Humidity drift (year 4 to 7), the most common wine cellar issue.</strong> Cellar holding temp but humidity dropping below 50% RH. Cause: condensate not returning to the cellar (drain reroutes humidity outside), or supplemental humidifier failure. Solution: rebalance defrost, sometimes humidification module service.</li>
      <li><strong>Multi-zone temperature drift</strong> (multi-zone systems): one zone drifts while others hold. Zone-specific thermostat or zone valve issue.</li>
      <li><strong>Compressor short-cycling</strong>: undersized system for actual cellar load (often happens after expansion of cellar inventory or addition of new cases beyond original spec).</li>
      <li><strong>Refrigerant leak.</strong> Wine cellar systems often run R-134a or R-410A (newer); some 2024+ Wine Guardian and CellarPro use R-454B (newest green refrigerant, requires R-454B-ready service).</li>
      <li><strong>Condenser issue</strong> (split systems with outdoor condensing unit, common for ducted Wine Guardian installs): outdoor unit fan or coil issue.</li>
      <li><strong>Air handler / evaporator fan failure</strong> (ducted systems): duct cooling stops reaching the cellar.</li>
      <li><strong>Door gasket compression</strong> (cellar door, walk-in style cellars): even small gasket leaks dramatically affect humidity.</li>
      <li><strong>Drain line blockage / drain pan heater failure</strong> (cold cellars): water pooling, sometimes ice formation.</li>
      <li><strong>Smart controls / WiFi monitoring failure</strong> (modern Wine Guardian, CellarPro, KoolR models): control system drift even though refrigeration is working.</li>
      <li><strong>Vibration issues.</strong> Wine doesn't tolerate vibration. Premium systems have vibration isolation that can degrade, transmitting fan or compressor vibration into the cellar racking.</li>
    </ol>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 03 ARCHITECTURE TYPES -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">03 · Wine cellar architecture types</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Four configurations, four service trees.</h2>

    <div class="arch-block">
      <h3>Self-contained through-the-wall units</h3>
      <p><strong>Brands:</strong> Breezaire WKL/WKLH, CellarPro 1800, 2200, 4200 series.</p>
      <p>Single unit, mounted through the wall of the cellar. Compressor and evaporator combined. Easier service access, but heat is rejected into the adjacent room (which has to be a non-conditioned space or you create a thermal load loop). Limited capacity, suited for small to medium cellars under 1,000 cu ft.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="arch-block">
      <h3>Ducted split systems</h3>
      <p><strong>Brands:</strong> Wine Guardian D-Series, CellarPro Ducted variants.</p>
      <p>Air handler in the cellar, condensing unit elsewhere (basement, mechanical room, or outdoor). Higher capacity and quieter cellar than self-contained. More complex service: line set work, ductwork, controls. Most premium restaurant installs use this configuration.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="arch-block">
      <h3>Ductless split systems (mini-split)</h3>
      <p><strong>Brands:</strong> Wine Guardian Mini-Split, KoolR.</p>
      <p>Indoor unit on the cellar wall, outdoor condenser elsewhere. High efficiency, multi-zone capable. Premium hotel and restaurant cellars often spec ductless because of the efficiency profile and the cleaner cellar aesthetic.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="arch-block">
      <h3>Custom built-in systems</h3>
      <p>Architect-designed systems with custom specs. Service requires reading the original installation specs and understanding the engineer's design intent. We coordinate with the original installer when possible; when not, we work from the as-built documentation and field measurements.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 04 REAL REPAIR STORIES -->
<section class="section section-gray">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">04 · Recent wine cellar repairs</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">Composite stories from the route.</h2>

    <p class="lead">Five wine cellar cooling jobs from the past 90 days. Models, symptoms, diagnosis, parts, time, total. Names omitted; the technical scenarios are typical of what we see weekly.</p>

    <div class="story-grid">
      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>High-end restaurant in Beverly Hills · Wine Guardian D050 ducted split, 6 years old, R-410A</h3>
        <p>Humidity dropped to 38% RH (target 60%). Wine staff worried about cork integrity on $200K+ inventory. Diagnosed: condensate drain rerouted during recent kitchen renovation now exits outside the cellar, taking humidity with it. Rerouted drain back into cellar (sealed condensate basin), added supplemental humidification module. Humidity stabilized at 58% RH within 48 hours. Total: $120 + $480 humidification module + $480 labor = $1,080.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Hotel in Santa Monica · CellarPro 4200VSi self-contained, 5 years old, R-134a</h3>
        <p>Temp climbing to 68°F. Diagnosed: refrigerant leak at evap coil joint. EPA 608 leak repair: pumped down, brazed joint, evacuated to 500 microns, recharged R-134a. Pulldown to 55°F over 8 hours. Total: $120 + $380 refrigerant + $580 labor = $1,080.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Restaurant in West Hollywood · Vinotemp custom multi-zone, 9 years old</h3>
        <p>Red wine zone at 62°F, white wine zone normal at 51°F. Diagnosed: red zone thermostat drift (multi-zone systems have separate thermostats per zone). Recalibrated thermostat to red wine spec. No parts needed. Monitored 48 hours, stable. Total: $120 + 1.5 hours labor = $360.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Country club in Calabasas · Wine Guardian D200 industrial-tier ducted, 11 years old</h3>
        <p>Air handler in the cellar making vibration noise. Diagnosed: evaporator fan motor bearings worn (cellar staff noticed wine bottles in the nearest rack vibrating). Replaced fan motor with vibration-isolated mount. Total: $120 + $480 motor + $390 labor = $990.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="story-card">
        <h3>Boutique restaurant in Pasadena · Breezaire WKL-4000 through-the-wall, 8 years old</h3>
        <p>Making excessive noise plus cellar warming. Diagnosed: condenser fan motor bearings shot plus refrigerant slightly low. Replaced motor, added 4 oz R-134a top-off. Total: $120 + $290 motor + $180 refrigerant top-off + 1.5 hours labor = $760.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<!-- 05 HONEST SCOPE -->
<section class="section">
  <div class="container narrow">
    <p class="section-number">05 · Honest scope</p>
    <h2 class="section-title">What we service, what we don't.</h2>

    <p><strong>We service:</strong></p>
    <ul class="bullet-list">
      <li>Wine Guardian (D-Series, S-Series, mini-split, all configurations)</li>
      <li>CellarPro (1800, 2200, 4200 self-contained, ducted, mini-split)</li>
      <li>KoolR premium custom systems</li>
